{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534048"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:41:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:41:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14888"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14888"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.08,0.21,0.07,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59191"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7579"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44602"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4384"},{"type":"tags","id":"4532"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"7970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43568"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59191"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic at 20 weeks\u0027 gestation after her three-year-old child was diagnosed with erythema infectiosum (fifth disease) one week ago. She reports having had a mild fever and rash two days ago. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a faint lacy rash on her arms and trunk. Investigations reveal positive parvovirus B19 IgM and DNA.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Weekly ultrasound for 12 weeks","Single ultrasound in two weeks","Monthly ultrasound until delivery","Immediate intrauterine transfusion","Reassurance only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis pregnant woman has acute parvovirus B19 infection, confirmed by positive IgM and DNA testing. The main concern in pregnancy is the risk of transmission to the fetus, which can lead to severe complications including fetal anaemia, hydrops fetalis, and fetal death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeekly ultrasound for 12 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. This allows monitoring for signs of fetal anaemia and hydrops, which typically develop 2-12 weeks after maternal infection. Signs to monitor include increased middle cerebral artery peak systolic velocity (suggesting fetal anaemia) and evidence of hydrops such as ascites, pleural effusions, or skin oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance only\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate given the significant risk of fetal complications. While many fetuses will not be affected, the potential consequences are severe enough to warrant close monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle ultrasound in two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient as fetal complications can develop any time within the 12-week risk period after maternal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonthly ultrasound until delivery\u003C/strong\u003E extends monitoring beyond the period of highest risk. After 12 weeks post-infection, if no complications have developed, the risk of subsequent problems is very low.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate intrauterine transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E would only be indicated if there were already signs of fetal anaemia or hydrops, which are not present in this case. This invasive procedure carries risks and should be reserved for cases with evidence of fetal compromise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Parvovirus B19 infection in pregnancy can cause severe fetal anaemia and hydrops fetalis requiring close ultrasound surveillance.","Weekly ultrasound monitoring is required for 12 weeks after maternal parvovirus infection in pregnancy.","Intrauterine transfusion may be required if fetal hydrops develops due to parvovirus infection."],"references":["Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases (ASID). Management of perinatal infections. East Melbourne: ASID; 2022 [cited 2024 Nov 5]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44602"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14888"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44602"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-05T15:23:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T15:24:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7579"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59191"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":